{"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language\/AboutTheLanguageReference"},"sections":[],"kind":"article","schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"major":0,"patch":0},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language"]]},"metadata":{"title":"About the Language Reference"},"abstract":[{"text":"Read the notation that the formal grammar uses.","type":"text"}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This part of the book describes the formal grammar of the Swift programming language."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"The grammar described here is intended to help you understand the language in more","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"detail, rather than to allow you to directly implement a parser or compiler."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The Swift language is relatively small, because many common types, functions, and operators"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that appear virtually everywhere in Swift code","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"are actually defined in the Swift standard library. Although these types, functions,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"and operators aren’t part of the Swift language itself,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"they’re used extensively in the discussions and code examples in this part of the book."}]},{"anchor":"How-to-Read-the-Grammar","level":2,"text":"How to Read the Grammar","type":"heading"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The notation used to describe the formal grammar of the Swift programming language","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"follows a few conventions:","type":"text"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"An arrow (→) is used to mark grammar productions and can be read as “can consist of.”"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Syntactic categories are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"italic","type":"text"}]},{"text":" text and appear on both sides","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Literal words and punctuation are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"boldface constant width"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"and appear only on the right-hand side of a grammar production rule."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Alternative grammar productions are separated by vertical"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"bars (|). When alternative productions are too long to read easily,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"they’re broken into multiple grammar production rules on new lines.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In a few cases, regular font text is used to describe the right-hand side"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Optional syntactic categories and literals are marked by a trailing","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"question mark, ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}]},{"type":"text","text":"."}]}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"As an example, the grammar of a getter-setter block is defined as follows:"}]},{"type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":""}]},{"inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"{","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"strong"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}]},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]},{"type":"text","text":" | "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"{","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","style":"note"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This definition indicates that a getter-setter block can consist of a getter clause","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"followed by an optional setter clause, enclosed in braces,"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"or"}]},{"text":" a setter clause followed by a getter clause, enclosed in braces.","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"The grammar production above is equivalent to the following two productions,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"where the alternatives are spelled out explicitly:","type":"text"}]},{"style":"note","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":""}]},{"inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-setter-block","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" → ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"\n","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"{","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}]}],"type":"paragraph"}],"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block"}],"kind":"content"}],"references":{"doc://org.swift.tspl/documentation/The-Swift-Programming-Language":{"kind":"article","url":"\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language","identifier":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language","type":"topic","role":"collection","title":"The Swift Programming Language (5.9)","abstract":[]}}}